    "summarizer": {
      "general_reader_takeaway": "This paper proposes a new way to track how particles move through space when gravity is described quantum-mechanically. Instead of the usual approach of averaging the warped geometry first and then computing a path, the authors argue for averaging a different geometric quantity \u2014 the affine connection \u2014 to get richer information. The review board found the high-level idea physically motivated and the paper peer-reviewed in a reputable journal, but could not audit the derivations because the full article body was unavailable to reviewers. The most important open question is whether the proposed equations are physically meaningful independent of arbitrary coordinate choices.",
      "reviewer": "claude",
      "technical_takeaway": "Koch, Riahinia, and Rincon (PRD 112, 084056, Oct 2025) introduce \"q-desics\" by grounding test-particle equations of motion in \u27e8\u0393^\u03bc_\u03bd\u03c1\u27e9 \u2014 the expectation value of the affine connection operator \u2014 rather than in \u0393^\u03bc_\u03bd\u03c1(\u27e8g\u27e9), the connection built from the expectation metric. The paper claims this captures Jensen-inequality-type corrections missed by the standard semiclassical approach, derives the q-desic equation via both Lagrangian and Hamiltonian methods, and applies it to spherically symmetric canonical quantum-gravity backgrounds. All three reviewers identified the same unresolved abstract-level concerns: (1) the affine connection is not a generally covariant tensor, so \u27e8\u0393\u27e9 is coordinate-dependent and covariance of the q-desic equation must be established; (2) whether the resulting equation follows from a well-defined variational principle and whether \u27e8\u0393\u27e9 is metric-compatible are unaddressed; (3) the claim of corrections \"far above the Planck scale\" is semantically ambiguous relative to standard EFT expectations. None of these could be resolved because the article body was absent from the review bundle."
    }
